---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import ProductCard from '../components/ProductCard.astro'
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Best Generators for Home Use — Buying Guide & Reviews"
  description="Find the right generator for your home. We compare portable, inverter, dual-fuel, and standby generators by wattage, fuel type, and price. Updated reviews and top picks."
>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="threat-hero">
    <div class="hero-img-wrap">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1621905251189-08b45d6a269e?w=1600&q=80&fit=crop" alt="Home generator" class="hero-img" />
      <div class="hero-overlay"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="container hero-content">
      <div class="hero-label">Home Protection · Generators</div>
      <h1>Find the Right Generator for Your Home</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Power outages after storms can last days or weeks. The right generator keeps your
        sump pump running, your food cold, and your family safe. Here's how to choose.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href="#picks" class="btn btn-primary">See Top Picks</a>
        <a href="#sizing" class="btn btn-secondary">What Size Do I Need?</a>
        <a href="#types" class="btn btn-text">Compare Generator Types →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Key facts -->
  <div class="key-facts">
    <div class="container facts-row">
      <div class="fact">
        <div class="fact-value">$600–$1,500</div>
        <div class="fact-label">Typical portable generator cost</div>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-divider"></div>
      <div class="fact">
        <div class="fact-value">5,000–7,500W</div>
        <div class="fact-label">Right size for most homes</div>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-divider"></div>
      <div class="fact">
        <div class="fact-value">20 feet</div>
        <div class="fact-label">Minimum distance from home (CO safety)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-divider"></div>
      <div class="fact">
        <div class="fact-value">Buy early</div>
        <div class="fact-label">Generators sell out when storms form</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Tab strip -->
  <nav class="section-tabs">
    <div class="container tabs-row">
      <a href="#types" class="tab">Generator Types</a>
      <a href="#sizing" class="tab">Sizing Guide</a>
      <a href="#picks" class="tab">Top Picks</a>
      <a href="#portable" class="tab">Portable</a>
      <a href="#inverter" class="tab">Inverter</a>
      <a href="#dualfuel" class="tab">Dual Fuel</a>
      <a href="#standby" class="tab">Standby</a>
      <a href="#safety" class="tab">Safety</a>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- Main layout -->
  <div class="container page-layout">

    <article class="article">

      <p class="lead">
        Choosing the wrong generator is expensive and frustrating. Too small and it won't
        run what you need. Too large and you're wasting money and fuel. This guide helps
        you find exactly what your home requires — and avoid the most common mistakes.
      </p>

      <!-- Part 1 -->
      <div class="part-heading" id="types">
        <div class="part-number">Part 1</div>
        <h2 class="part-title">Understanding Generator Types</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="type-grid">
        <div class="type-card">
          <div class="type-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
              <rect x="8" y="16" width="32" height="20" rx="2" stroke="#1B3A52" stroke-width="2" fill="#EBF4FB"/>
              <path d="M16 16V12M32 16V12" stroke="#1B3A52" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <circle cx="18" cy="26" r="4" stroke="#2E7CB8" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <circle cx="30" cy="26" r="4" stroke="#2E7CB8" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 36L36 36" stroke="#D4691E" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Portable</h3>
          <div class="type-range">$400–$1,200</div>
          <p>The most common choice. Runs on gasoline, requires manual setup and refueling. Good for powering essential circuits.</p>
          <div class="type-best">Best for: Budget-conscious buyers, occasional use</div>
        </div>

        <div class="type-card type-card-featured">
          <div class="type-badge">Most Popular</div>
          <div class="type-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
              <rect x="8" y="16" width="32" height="20" rx="2" stroke="#1B3A52" stroke-width="2" fill="#EBF4FB"/>
              <path d="M20 22L24 26L28 18" stroke="#2E7CB8" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              <path d="M12 36L36 36" stroke="#D4691E" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <circle cx="38" cy="14" r="5" fill="#D4691E" opacity="0.2" stroke="#D4691E" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M36 14H40M38 12V16" stroke="#D4691E" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Inverter</h3>
          <div class="type-range">$700–$2,000</div>
          <p>Produces clean, stable power safe for electronics. Quieter, more fuel-efficient, and lighter than conventional portables.</p>
          <div class="type-best">Best for: Sensitive electronics, quiet neighborhoods, RV use</div>
        </div>

        <div class="type-card">
          <div class="type-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
              <rect x="8" y="16" width="32" height="20" rx="2" stroke="#1B3A52" stroke-width="2" fill="#EBF4FB"/>
              <path d="M20 24H28M24 20V28" stroke="#2E7CB8" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <path d="M12 36L36 36" stroke="#D4691E" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <path d="M10 14C10 14 14 10 18 14M30 14C30 14 34 10 38 14" stroke="#1B3A52" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Dual Fuel</h3>
          <div class="type-range">$600–$1,500</div>
          <p>Runs on gasoline OR propane. Propane stores indefinitely — huge advantage when gas stations run out after a storm.</p>
          <div class="type-best">Best for: Hurricane-prone areas, long outages</div>
        </div>

        <div class="type-card">
          <div class="type-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
              <rect x="6" y="12" width="36" height="28" rx="2" stroke="#1B3A52" stroke-width="2" fill="#EBF4FB"/>
              <path d="M14 12V8M34 12V8" stroke="#1B3A52" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <rect x="14" y="20" width="20" height="12" rx="1" stroke="#2E7CB8" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M20 26H28M24 22V30" stroke="#2E7CB8" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Standby</h3>
          <div class="type-range">$5,000–$15,000 installed</div>
          <p>Permanently installed, starts automatically within seconds of a power outage. Runs on natural gas or propane indefinitely.</p>
          <div class="type-best">Best for: Whole-home coverage, medical equipment, frequent outages</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Part 2 -->
      <div class="part-heading" id="sizing">
        <div class="part-number">Part 2</div>
        <h2 class="part-title">What Size Generator Do You Need?</h2>
      </div>

      <p>Generator size is measured in watts. You need to add up the wattage of everything you want to run simultaneously. Here's a practical guide:</p>

      <table class="compare-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Appliance</th><th>Running Watts</th><th>Starting Watts</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Refrigerator</td><td>150–400W</td><td>800–1,200W</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Window AC (10,000 BTU)</td><td>1,200W</td><td>3,600W</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sump pump (1/2 HP)</td><td>800W</td><td>2,000W</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Well pump (1/2 HP)</td><td>1,000W</td><td>2,100W</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lights (10 x LED)</td><td>100W</td><td>100W</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Phone/laptop chargers</td><td>200W</td><td>200W</td></tr>
          <tr><td>CPAP machine</td><td>30–60W</td><td>30–60W</td></tr>
          <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Typical essential load</strong></td><td><strong>~3,500W</strong></td><td><strong>~7,000W</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="sizing-cards">
        <div class="sizing-card">
          <div class="sizing-watt">3,500–5,000W</div>
          <h3>Essential Only</h3>
          <p>Refrigerator, lights, phone charging, and a fan. No AC. Minimal comfort but keeps food safe and devices charged.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sizing-card sizing-card-rec">
          <div class="sizing-badge">Recommended</div>
          <div class="sizing-watt">5,000–7,500W</div>
          <h3>Comfortable Living</h3>
          <p>Everything above plus a window AC unit and sump pump. Handles most homes' essential needs during an extended outage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sizing-card">
          <div class="sizing-watt">10,000W+</div>
          <h3>Whole Home</h3>
          <p>Central AC, electric range, and everything else. Usually requires a transfer switch and professional installation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Starting vs. running watts:</strong> Motors (AC units, pumps) require 2–3x their running wattage to start. Always size your generator based on the highest starting watt load you'll run, not just the running watts.
      </div>

      <!-- Part 3: Top Picks -->
      <div class="part-heading" id="picks">
        <div class="part-number">Part 3</div>
        <h2 class="part-title">Our Top Generator Picks</h2>
      </div>

      <p>These are the generators we recommend most based on reliability, value, and real-world performance during extended outages.</p>

      <!-- Portable -->
      <div class="section-block" id="portable">
        <h2>Best Portable Generators</h2>
        <p>Portable generators are the right choice for most homeowners. They're affordable, easy to store, and provide enough power to keep essentials running during an outage.</p>
        <div class="product-row">
          <ProductCard
            name="WEN 56200i 2000W Inverter Generator"
            asin="B07GBKFYQM"
            price="$399"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Budget Pick"
            desc="Quiet, lightweight, and fuel-efficient. Great for essential charging and small appliances. Ideal for apartments or as a backup to a larger unit."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="Champion 3500W Portable Generator"
            asin="B07GBKFYQM"
            price="$489"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Best Value"
            desc="Reliable workhorse at a fair price. Handles refrigerator, sump pump, and lights simultaneously. Easy electric start."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="Generac GP6500 6,500W Generator"
            asin="B01IRQMIDI"
            price="$849"
            store="amazon"
            desc="6,500 running watts handles most home essentials including a window AC. PowerRush technology provides extra starting power."
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Inverter -->
      <div class="section-block" id="inverter">
        <h2>Best Inverter Generators</h2>
        <p>Inverter generators produce clean, stable power — safe for phones, laptops, and medical equipment. They're quieter and more fuel-efficient than conventional portables.</p>
        <div class="product-row">
          <ProductCard
            name="Honda EU2200i 2,200W Inverter"
            asin="B077K3BKPV"
            price="$1,099"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Editor's Pick"
            desc="The gold standard. Incredibly quiet (48–57 dB), runs 8+ hours on 1 gallon. Honda reliability means it starts every time. Worth every penny."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="Yamaha EF2200iS 2,200W Inverter"
            asin="B07GBKFYQM"
            price="$999"
            store="amazon"
            desc="Honda's closest competitor. Equally quiet and reliable. Smart Throttle automatically adjusts engine speed to match load — extends run time significantly."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="WEN 56200i Super Quiet 2000W"
            asin="B07GBKFYQM"
            price="$449"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Budget Inverter"
            desc="Best budget inverter generator. Clean power for electronics at half the price of Honda. Runs 6 hours on 1 gallon at 50% load."
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Dual Fuel -->
      <div class="section-block" id="dualfuel">
        <h2>Best Dual Fuel Generators</h2>
        <p>Dual fuel generators run on gasoline OR propane. In a hurricane, when gas stations are closed or have hour-long lines, propane from your grill tank keeps you running.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Propane advantage:</strong> Propane stores indefinitely with no fuel stabilizer needed. Stock up before hurricane season and you're always ready.
        </div>

        <div class="product-row">
          <ProductCard
            name="Champion 7,500W Dual Fuel Generator"
            asin="B07FDQJRBT"
            price="$729"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Top Pick"
            desc="The best all-around dual fuel generator. 7,500W on gas, 6,750W on propane. Electric start, low-oil shutoff, runs 8 hrs at 50% load."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="DuroMax XP5500EH Dual Fuel"
            asin="B07GBKFYQM"
            price="$579"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Best Value"
            desc="5,500W at a great price. Quieter than most at this wattage. EPA and CARB compliant — ships to all 50 states."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="Westinghouse WGen9500DF Dual Fuel"
            asin="B07GBKFYQM"
            price="$1,099"
            store="amazon"
            desc="9,500W peak power handles central AC and whole-home essentials. Remote start key fob included. Best for larger homes."
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Standby -->
      <div class="section-block" id="standby">
        <h2>Standby Generators</h2>
        <p>
          A standby generator is a permanent installation connected to your home's electrical
          panel and natural gas or propane line. It detects a power outage and starts
          automatically — usually within 10–30 seconds — without any action from you.
        </p>
        <p>
          Standby generators are the right choice if you have medical equipment, a home
          office, or live in an area with frequent or extended outages. They require
          licensed electrical and gas installation and typically cost $5,000–$15,000 all-in.
        </p>

        <div class="callout callout-blue">
          <strong>Generac dominates this category.</strong> They manufacture roughly 70% of standby home generators sold in the US. Kohler and Briggs & Stratton are also strong options. Get 3 quotes from licensed installers — installation cost varies significantly by location.
        </div>

        <div class="product-row product-row-2">
          <ProductCard
            name="Generac 7043 22kW Air-Cooled Standby Generator"
            asin="B01N9DNOVT"
            price="$4,299"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Best Standby"
            desc="22kW powers a large home completely. WiFi monitoring via Generac Mobile Link app. Runs on natural gas or LP. Professional installation required."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="Generac 7172 11kW Air-Cooled Standby Generator"
            asin="B07GBKFYQM"
            price="$2,699"
            store="amazon"
            desc="Right-sized for most homes up to 2,500 sq ft. Quieter than larger units. Includes automatic transfer switch. Most popular residential standby."
          />
        </div>

        <div class="installer-note">
          <h3>Finding a Qualified Installer</h3>
          <p>Standby generator installation requires a licensed electrician and gas plumber. Use Generac's dealer locator or HomeAdvisor to find certified installers in your area. Always get at least three quotes — installation costs range from $1,500 to $5,000+ depending on your panel setup and gas line distance.</p>
          <a href="https://www.generac.com/for-homeowners/generac-dealers" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn btn-outline" style="margin-top:16px; display:inline-block;">Find a Generac Dealer →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Safety -->
      <div class="section-block" id="safety">
        <h2>Generator Safety</h2>

        <div class="callout callout-red">
          <strong>Carbon monoxide kills.</strong> Generators produce CO — a colorless, odorless gas that kills within minutes at high concentrations. Every year people die from running generators indoors. This is non-negotiable.
        </div>

        <ul class="action-list">
          <li>Never run a generator inside your home, garage, basement, or carport — even with the door open</li>
          <li>Position at least 20 feet from any window, door, or vent</li>
          <li>Install battery-operated CO detectors on every level of your home</li>
          <li>Point the exhaust away from your home and neighbors</li>
          <li>Never refuel while running — let it cool for 15 minutes first</li>
          <li>Use a transfer switch or interlock kit — never backfeed into your panel</li>
          <li>Store fuel safely in approved containers, away from the generator</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="product-row product-row-2" style="margin-top:24px;">
          <ProductCard
            name="Kidde Nighthawk CO Detector"
            asin="B00002N67S"
            price="$34"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Essential"
            desc="Install one on every level of your home when running a generator. Battery backup means it works even during a power outage."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="Reliance Controls 31410CRK Transfer Switch Kit"
            asin="B000E1HNZS"
            price="$89"
            store="amazon"
            desc="Safe, code-compliant way to connect your generator to your home's circuits. Much safer than extension cords for whole-home use."
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Checklist CTA -->
      <div class="checklist-cta" id="checklist">
        <h2>Free Generator Buying Checklist</h2>
        <p>Calculate your wattage needs, compare fuel types, and know exactly what to ask an installer. Enter your email and we'll send it right away.</p>
        <form class="cta-form" name="generator-checklist" method="POST" data-netlify="true">
          <input type="hidden" name="form-name" value="generator-checklist" />
          <input type="email" name="email" placeholder="your@email.com" required />
          <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Send Me the Checklist</button>
        </form>
      </div>

    </article>

    <!-- Sidebar -->
    <aside class="sidebar">

      <div class="sb-card">
        <h4>On This Page</h4>
        <a href="#types">Generator Types</a>
        <a href="#sizing">Sizing Guide</a>
        <a href="#picks">Top Picks</a>
        <a href="#portable">Portable</a>
        <a href="#inverter">Inverter</a>
        <a href="#dualfuel">Dual Fuel</a>
        <a href="#standby">Standby</a>
        <a href="#safety">Safety</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sb-card sb-alert">
        <h4>Buy Before the Storm</h4>
        <p>Generators sell out within hours of a named storm. Stock up before hurricane season — not when a storm is forecast.</p>
      </div>

      <h4 class="sb-section-label">Related Guides</h4>

      <a href="/hurricanes" class="sb-visual-card">
        <div class="sb-visual-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1563089145-599997674d42?w=300&q=80&fit=crop" alt="Hurricane guide" />
          <div class="sb-visual-overlay"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="sb-visual-label">Hurricane Guide →</div>
      </a>

      <a href="/backup-power" class="sb-visual-card">
        <div class="sb-visual-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1548438294-1ad5d5f4f063?w=300&q=80&fit=crop" alt="Backup power" />
          <div class="sb-visual-overlay"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="sb-visual-label">Backup Power Guide →</div>
      </a>

      <a href="/emergency-kits" class="sb-visual-card">
        <div class="sb-visual-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1584308666744-24d5c474f2ae?w=300&q=80&fit=crop" alt="Emergency kits" />
          <div class="sb-visual-overlay"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="sb-visual-label">Emergency Kits →</div>
      </a>

      <div class="sb-card">
        <h4>Quick Size Guide</h4>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem; color:var(--text-mid); margin-bottom:10px;">Add up what you need to run:</p>
        <div class="quick-calc">
          <div class="calc-row"><span>Refrigerator</span><span>400W</span></div>
          <div class="calc-row"><span>Window AC</span><span>1,200W</span></div>
          <div class="calc-row"><span>Sump pump</span><span>800W</span></div>
          <div class="calc-row"><span>Lights + devices</span><span>300W</span></div>
          <div class="calc-row calc-total"><span>Typical total</span><span>~5,500W</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </aside>

  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<script>
  const sections = ['types','sizing','picks','portable','inverter','dualfuel','standby','safety']
  const tabs = document.querySelectorAll('.section-tabs .tab')

  const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
    entries.forEach(entry => {
      if (entry.isIntersecting) {
        tabs.forEach(t => t.classList.remove('active'))
        const activeTab = document.querySelector(`.tab[href="#${entry.target.id}"]`)
        if (activeTab) activeTab.classList.add('active')
      }
    })
  }, { rootMargin: '-20% 0px -70% 0px' })

  sections.forEach(id => {
    const el = document.getElementById(id)
    if (el) observer.observe(el)
  })
</script>

<style>
  .threat-hero { position: relative; height: 480px; display: flex; align-items: center; overflow: hidden; }
  .hero-img-wrap { position: absolute; inset: 0; z-index: 0; }
  .hero-img { width: 100%; height: 100%; object-fit: cover; object-position: center; }
  .hero-overlay { position: absolute; inset: 0; background: linear-gradient(to right, rgba(13,35,56,0.92) 0%, rgba(13,35,56,0.65) 60%, rgba(13,35,56,0.3) 100%); }
  .hero-content { position: relative; z-index: 1; max-width: 640px; color: white; }
  .hero-label { font-size: 0.78rem; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.12em; color: #A8CEDF; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  .hero-content h1 { color: white; margin-bottom: 20px; }
  .hero-sub { font-size: 1.05rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 32px; max-width: 560px; }
  .hero-actions { display: flex; gap: 14px; align-items: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .btn-text { color: rgba(255,255,255,0.75); font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 500; text-decoration: none; transition: color 0.15s; }
  .btn-text:hover { color: white; text-decoration: none; }

  .key-facts { background: var(--off-white); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 24px 0; }
  .facts-row { display: flex; align-items: center; }
  .fact { flex: 1; padding: 0 32px; }
  .fact:first-child { padding-left: 0; }
  .fact-value { font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--navy); margin-bottom: 3px; }
  .fact-label { font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--text-light); }
  .fact-divider { width: 2px; height: 36px; background: var(--border); flex-shrink: 0; }

  .section-tabs { background: white; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border); position: sticky; top: 68px; z-index: 90; box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.06); }
  .tabs-row { display: flex; overflow-x: auto; scrollbar-width: none; }
  .tabs-row::-webkit-scrollbar { display: none; }
  .tab { font-size: 0.82rem; font-weight: 500; color: var(--text-mid); padding: 14px 20px; white-space: nowrap; text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 3px solid transparent; margin-bottom: -2px; transition: all 0.15s; border-right: 1.5px solid var(--border); }
  .tab:last-child { border-right: none; }
  .tab:hover { color: var(--sky); background: var(--sky-light); text-decoration: none; }
